Rather than pointing to specific variants, genome-wide association studies typically implicate loci containing many co-inherited variants. Because the signal is spread out over many variants, it is challenging to tell which are truly associated with risk. In this paper, we approach that problem with the underlying model that noncoding GWAS loci may sometimes point to regulatory regions that influence the trait. So, we integrated cardiomyopathy GWAS data with open chromatin data we generated from engineered heart tubes. This allowed us to prioritize likely functional variants and enhancers, which we then validated in hiPSC-CMs and engineered heart tubes, establishing this model system and approach as a tractible means to dissect noncoding GWAS loci.
